in b&aacute;nh cuÃ¡Â»â€˜n is extremely thin and delicate. It is a light dish, and is generally eaten for breakfast everywhere in Vietnam. A different version of b&aacute;nh cuÃ¡Â»â€˜n, called b&aacute;nh cuÃ¡Â»â€˜n Thanh Tr&igrave; and b&aacute;nh cuÃ¡Â»â€˜n l&agrave;ng K&ecirc;nh, may be found in Thanh Tr&igrave;, a southern district of Hanoi and K&ecirc;nh village of Nam Ã„ï¿½Ã¡Â»â€¹nh, an ancient village in the centre of Nam Ã„ï¿½Ã¡Â»â€¹nh city.B&aacute;nh cuÃ¡Â»â€˜n Thanh Tr&igrave; or B&aacute;nh cuÃ¡Â»â€˜n l&agrave;ng K&ecirc;nh are not rolls, but just rice sheets eaten with chÃ¡ÂºÂ£ lÃ¡Â»Â¥a, fried shallots, or prawns; see the article B&aacute;nh cuÃ¡Â»â€˜n in the Vietnamese Wikipedia.<br /><br />A similar Chinese dish is the Cantonese dish coeng4 fan2 (Ã¨â€šÂ Ã§Â²â€°; pinyin: ch&aacute;ngfÃ„â€ºn), usually translated into English as \"steamed rice roll\" or \"rice noodle roll,\" which is a form of dim sum.</p>','Wikipedia','','/upload/news/admin/2010/08/4c7cc45c523c6_square.jpg','/upload/news/admin/2010/08/4c7cc45c523c6_thumbnail.jpg','/upload/news/admin/2010/08/4c7cc45c523c6_small.jpg','/upload/news/admin/2010/08/4c7cc45c523c6_crop.jpg','/upload/news/admin/2010/08/4c7cc45c523c6_medium.jpg','/upload/news/admin/2010/08/4c7cc45c523c6_large.jpg','active',2,'2010-08-31 15:59:15',1,'admin','2010-08-31 16:03:19',1,'admin',1,'admin','2010-08-31 15:59:26',0,0,0,0,NULL,0,'en_US'),(24,17,'BÃƒÂ¡nh cuÃ¡Â»â€˜n','','banh-cuon','<p>B&aacute;nh cuÃ¡Â»â€˜n hay b&aacute;nh Ã†Â°Ã¡Â»â€ºt l&agrave; loÃ¡ÂºÂ¡i b&aacute;nh l&agrave;m tÃ¡Â»Â« bÃ¡Â»â„¢t gÃ¡ÂºÂ¡o hÃ¡ÂºÂ¥p tr&aacute;ng mÃ¡Â»ï¿½ng, Ã„â€˜Ã¡Â»Æ’ Ã„Æ’n khi c&ograve;n Ã†Â°Ã¡Â»â€ºt, trong c&oacute; thÃ¡Â»Æ’ cuÃ¡Â»â€˜n nh&acirc;n hoÃ¡ÂºÂ·c kh&ocirc;ng nh&acirc;n (kh&aacute;c vÃ¡Â»â€ºi b&aacute;nh tr&aacute;ng, (b&aacute;nh Ã„â€˜a) phÃ¡ÂºÂ£i phÃ†Â¡i kh&ocirc;; hay b&aacute;nh Ã†Â°Ã¡Â»â€ºt Ã¡Â»Å¸ miÃ¡Â»ï¿½n Nam. B&aacute;nh thÃ†Â°Ã¡Â»ï¿½ng Ã„Æ’n vÃ¡Â»â€ºi mÃ¡Â»â„¢t loÃ¡ÂºÂ¡i nÃ†Â°Ã¡Â»â€ºc chÃ¡ÂºÂ¥m pha nhÃ¡ÂºÂ¡t tÃ¡Â»Â« nÃ†Â°Ã¡Â