It is garnished with the lemony-scented herb ng&ograve; &ocirc;m (Limnophila aromatica), caramelized garlic, and chopped scallions, as well as other herbs, according to the specific variety of canh chua; these other herbs may include rau rÃ„Æ’m (Vietnamese coriander), ng&ograve; gai (long coriander), and rau quÃ¡ÂºÂ¿ (Thai basil).<br /><br />The sour taste of the soup comes from tamarind, which is mixed with a small amount of hot water; the mixture is then stirred for a few moments to release all the essence, and the liquid (minus the tamarind seeds and other solids, which are discarded) is then added to the soup.<br /><br />When made in style of a hot pot, canh chua is called lÃ¡ÂºÂ©u canh chua.</p>','Wikipedia','','/upload/news/admin/2010/08/4c7cda8d94a50_square.jpg','/upload/news/admin/2010/08/4c7cda8d94a50_thumbnail.jpg','/upload/news/admin/2010/08/4c7cda8d94a50_small.jpg','/upload/news/admin/2010/08/4c7cda8d94a50_crop.jpg','/upload/news/admin/2010/08/4c7cda8d94a50_medium.jpg','/upload/news/admin/2010/08/4c7cda8d94a50_large.jpg','active',1,'2010-08-31 17:33:55',1,'admin',NULL,NULL,NULL,1,'admin','2010-08-31 17:34:04',0,0,0,0,NULL,0,'en_US'),(34,17,'Canh chua','','canh-chua','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Canh chua l&agrave; t&ecirc;n gÃ¡Â»ï¿½i cÃ¡Â»Â§a nhÃ¡Â»Â¯ng m&oacute;n Ã„Æ’n nhiÃ¡Â»ï¿½u nÃ†Â°Ã¡Â»â€ºc v&agrave; c&oacute; vÃ¡Â»â€¹ chua do Ã„â€˜Ã†Â°Ã¡Â»Â£c nÃ¡ÂºÂ¥u bÃ¡ÂºÂ±ng c&aacute;c nguy&ecirc;n liÃ¡Â»â€¡u phÃ¡Â»â€˜i trÃ¡Â»â„¢n vÃ¡Â»â€ºi gia vÃ¡Â»â€¹ tÃ¡ÂºÂ¡o chua.</p>','<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"/upload/news/admin/2010/08/4c7cd9c2e4dfa_crop.jpg\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><em>MÃ¡Â»â„¢t b&aacute;t <em>canh chua</em></em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Canh chua thÃ†Â°Ã¡Â»ï¿½ng Ã„â€˜Ã†Â°Ã¡Â»Â£c d&ugrave;ng Ã¡Â»Å¸ nhÃ¡Â»Â¯ng v&ugrave;ng n&oacute;ng nhÃ†Â° miÃ¡Â»ï¿½n Nam, miÃ¡Â»ï¿½n Trung, hoÃ¡ÂºÂ·c nhÃ¡Â»Â¯ng l&uacute;c n&oacute;ng nÃ¡Â»Â±c cÃ¡Â»Â§a m&ugrave;a h&egrave