val in Tainan, Taiwan.</em></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">In some region and countries, this festival is also regarded as the Chinese version of St. Valentine\'s Day, a day celebrating love and affection between lovers in Chinese tradition and culture.</p>','Wikipedia','','2010-08-31 17:33:02',1,'admin'),(100,33,2,'Canh chua','','canh-chua','<p>Canh chua (literally \"sour soup\") is a sour soup indigenous to the Mekong River region of southern Vietnam.</p>','<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"http://phuocnh/amancms/upload/news/admin/2010/08/4c7cd9c2e4dfa_crop.jpg\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><em>A bowl of <em>canh chua</em></em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>It is typically made with fish from the Mekong River, pineapple, amanes (and sometimes also other vegetables such as okra or bÃ¡ÂºÂ¡c h&agrave;), and bean sprouts, in a tamarind-flavored broth. It is garnished with the lemony-scented herb ng&ograve; &ocirc;m (Limnophila aromatica), caramelized garlic, and chopped scallions, as well as other herbs, according to the specific variety of canh chua; these other herbs may include rau rÃ„Æ’m (Vietnamese coriander), ng&ograve; gai (long coriander), and rau quÃ¡ÂºÂ¿ (Thai basil).<br /><br />The sour taste of the soup comes from tamarind, which is mixed with a small amount of hot water; the mixture is then stirred for a few moments to release all the essence, and the liquid (minus the tamarind seeds and other solids, which are discarded) is then added to the soup.<br /><br />When made in style of a hot pot, canh chua is called lÃ¡ÂºÂ©u canh chua.</p>','Wikipedia','','2010-08-31 17:33:55',1,'admin'),(101,34,17,'Canh chua','','canh-chua','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Canh chua l&agrave; t&ecirc;n gÃ¡Â»ï¿½i cÃ¡Â»Â§a nhÃ¡Â»Â¯ng m&oacute;n Ã„Æ’n nhiÃ¡Â»ï¿½u nÃ†Â°Ã¡Â»â€ºc v&agrave; c&oacute; vÃ¡Â»â€¹ chua do Ã„â€˜Ã†Â°Ã¡Â»Â£c nÃ¡ÂºÂ¥u bÃ¡ÂºÂ±ng c&aacute;c nguy&ecirc;n l